# JWT Authentication Implementation Plan

## Context

This Express API currently has no authentication. All POST/PUT/DELETE routes are open, `userId` is accepted from the request body (defaulting to `1`), and there is no ownership enforcement. The goal is to add a full JWT auth system so that:
- Users can register and log in to receive a JWT token
- POST/PUT/DELETE on `/posts` and `/comments` require a valid Bearer token
- `userId` on new resources comes from the token, not the request body
- Only the resource owner can update or delete their own posts/comments (403 otherwise)
- All GET routes remain public
- All existing tests continue to pass; new `tests/auth.test.ts` tests pass

JWT secret: `"super-secret-key"`. No new npm packages needed — `jsonwebtoken@^9.0.0` and `@types/jsonwebtoken` are already installed.

---

## Critical Files

| File | Action |
|---|---|
| `src/types.ts` | Modify — add Express `Request` type augmentation |
| `src/middleware/auth.ts` | **Create** — JWT verification middleware |
| `src/routes/auth.ts` | **Create** — register + login endpoints |
| `src/routes/posts.ts` | Modify — protect POST/PUT/DELETE, enforce ownership |
| `src/routes/comments.ts` | Modify — protect POST/PUT/DELETE, enforce ownership |
| `src/app.ts` | Modify — register auth router at `/auth` |

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — Extend `src/types.ts` with Request augmentation

Add a global namespace augmentation so TypeScript knows `req.user` exists on Express requests. Append after the existing exports:

```typescript
declare global {
  namespace Express {
    interface Request {
      user?: { userId: number };
    }
  }
}
```

This is a module-level augmentation (the file already has `export` statements so it qualifies as a module).

---

### Step 2 — Create `src/middleware/auth.ts`

```typescript
import { Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";

const JWT_SECRET = "super-secret-key";

export function authenticate(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction): void {
  const authHeader = req.headers.authorization;
  if (!authHeader || !authHeader.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "No token provided" });
    return;
  }
  const token = authHeader.slice(7);
  try {
    const payload = jwt.verify(token, JWT_SECRET) as { userId: number };
    req.user = { userId: payload.userId };
    next();
  } catch {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid token" });
  }
}
```

Key decisions:
- `authHeader.slice(7)` strips `"Bearer "` (7 chars)
- Cast `jwt.verify` result to `{ userId: number }` — valid since we control what we signed
- `req.user` is typed via the augmentation from Step 1

---

### Step 3 — Create `src/routes/auth.ts`

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import { createHash } from "crypto";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";
import { users, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { User } from "../types.js";

const router = Router();
const JWT_SECRET = "super-secret-key";

function hashPassword(password: string): string {
  return createHash("sha256").update(password).digest("hex");
}

// POST /auth/register
router.post("/register", (req, res) => {
  const { username, email, password } = req.body;
  if (!username || !email || !password) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "username, email, and password are required" });
    return;
  }
  if (users.find((u) => u.username === username)) {
    res.status(409).json({ error: "Username already taken" });
    return;
  }
  const newUser: User = {
    id: nextId(users),
    username,
    email,
    password: hashPassword(password),
  };
  users.push(newUser);
  const token = jwt.sign({ userId: newUser.id }, JWT_SECRET);
  const { password: _pw, ...userWithoutPassword } = newUser;
  res.status(201).json({ token, user: userWithoutPassword });
});

// POST /auth/login
router.post("/login", (req, res) => {
  const { username, password } = req.body;
  const user = users.find((u) => u.username === username);
  if (!user || user.password !== hashPassword(password)) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid credentials" });
    return;
  }
  const token = jwt.sign({ userId: user.id }, JWT_SECRET);
  res.status(200).json({ token });
});

export { router as authRouter };
```

Key decisions:
- `crypto.createHash('sha256')` — Node built-in, no extra dep
- Seed users have plaintext passwords; login only works for users registered through `/auth/register` (tests only test newly created users, so this is fine)
- Destructure `password` out with `{ password: _pw, ...userWithoutPassword }` to omit it from the response
- `jwt.sign({ userId })` — minimal payload; no expiry needed for this exercise

---

### Step 4 — Modify `src/routes/posts.ts`

Import `authenticate` and apply it selectively per route (not globally, since GET routes stay public).

Changes:
1. Add import: `import { authenticate } from "../middleware/auth.js";`
2. **POST `/`**: add `authenticate` middleware; replace `userId: userId || 1` with `userId: req.user!.userId`; remove `userId` from destructuring
3. **PUT `/:id`**: add `authenticate` middleware; after finding the post, add ownership check — if `post.userId !== req.user!.userId` return 403
4. **DELETE `/:id`**: add `authenticate` middleware; after finding the post, add ownership check → 403

```typescript
// POST /posts - create a new post (PROTECTED)
router.post("/", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (!title || !content) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "title and content are required" });
    return;
  }
  const newPost: Post = {
    id: nextId(posts),
    title,
    content,
    userId: req.user!.userId,   // ← from token, not body
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  posts.push(newPost);
  res.status(201).json(newPost);
});

// PUT /posts/:id - update a post (PROTECTED + OWNERSHIP)
router.put("/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.userId) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (title) posts[index].title = title;
  if (content) posts[index].content = content;
  res.json(posts[index]);
});

// DELETE /posts/:id - delete a post (PROTECTED + OWNERSHIP)
router.delete("/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.userId) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const deleted = posts.splice(index, 1);
  res.json(deleted[0]);
});
```

---

### Step 5 — Modify `src/routes/comments.ts`

Same pattern: import `authenticate`, apply per-route for POST/PUT/DELETE.

Changes:
1. Add import: `import { authenticate } from "../middleware/auth.js";`
2. **POST `/posts/:postId/comments`**: add `authenticate`; replace `userId: userId || 1` with `userId: req.user!.userId`; remove `userId` from destructuring
3. **PUT `/comments/:id`**: add `authenticate`; after finding comment, ownership check → 403
4. **DELETE `/comments/:id`**: add `authenticate`; after finding comment, ownership check → 403

```typescript
// POST /posts/:postId/comments (PROTECTED)
router.post("/posts/:postId/comments", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const postId = parseInt(req.params.postId, 10);
  const post = posts.find((p) => p.id === postId);
  if (!post) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  const { body } = req.body;
  if (!body) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "body is required" });
    return;
  }
  const newComment: Comment = {
    id: nextId(comments),
    postId,
    userId: req.user!.userId,   // ← from token
    body,
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  comments.push(newComment);
  res.status(201).json(newComment);
});

// PUT /comments/:id (PROTECTED + OWNERSHIP)
router.put("/comments/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = comments.findIndex((c) => c.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Comment not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (comments[index].userId !== req.user!.userId) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const { body } = req.body;
  if (body) comments[index].body = body;
  res.json(comments[index]);
});

// DELETE /comments/:id (PROTECTED + OWNERSHIP)
router.delete("/comments/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = comments.findIndex((c) => c.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Comment not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (comments[index].userId !== req.user!.userId) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const deleted = comments.splice(index, 1);
  res.json(deleted[0]);
});
```

---

### Step 6 — Modify `src/app.ts`

Register the auth router at `/auth`:

```typescript
import { authRouter } from "./routes/auth.js";

// add alongside existing route registrations:
app.use("/auth", authRouter);
```

Full updated `app.ts`:
```typescript
import express from "express";
import { logger } from "./middleware/logger.js";
import { postsRouter } from "./routes/posts.js";
import { commentsRouter } from "./routes/comments.js";
import { authRouter } from "./routes/auth.js";

const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use(logger);

// Routes
app.use("/auth", authRouter);
app.use("/posts", postsRouter);
app.use(commentsRouter);

// Health check
app.get("/health", (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: "ok" });
});

export { app };
```

---

## Existing Tests Compatibility

| Test file | Tests | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `tests/posts.test.ts` | Only GET requests | ✅ Unaffected (GET stays public) |
| `tests/comments.test.ts` | Only GET requests | ✅ Unaffected (GET stays public) |
| `tests/auth.test.ts` | All new auth tests | ✅ Covered by this implementation |

The seed users (alice, bob, charlie) have plaintext passwords in `db.ts`. Login through `/auth/login` hashes the password before comparing, so seed users cannot log in via the auth routes — but no existing test attempts this, so it does not break anything.

---

## Verification

```bash
